I guess I arrived late to the party, but I'll say what I have to say anyway. I get [http://www.google.com/search?lr=lang_en&tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Peter+de+la+Billiere%22+-wikipedia&tbs=,cdr:1,cd_min:Jan%201_2%201990&num=10 2,100] post-1990 English-language Google Book hits for this subject's name, of which [http://www.google.com/search?lr=lang_en&tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Peter+de+la+Billi%C3%A8re%22+-wikipedia+-Billiere&tbs=,cdr:1,cd_min:Jan%201_2%201990&num=10 379] contain the diacritic. That's a usage rate of 18 percent. This is an extremely high rate for diacritic usage. Compare this to [http://www.google.com/search?lr=lang_en&tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Bj%C3%B6rn+Borg%22+tennis+-wikipedia+-Bjorn&num=10 1,040]/[http://www.google.com/search?lr=lang_en&tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=%22Bjorn+Borg%22+tennis+-wikipedia&num=10 160,000] ===> 6.5 percent for "Björn Borg". As I favor a threshold of 10 percent, I would have voted "opposed." [[User:Kauffner|Kauffner]] ([[User talk:Kauffner|talk]]) 10:10, 4 November 2011 (UTC)
